...
```
Wait, `SimplifyDemandedUseFPClass` is a recursive function.
Let's look at `simplifyDemandedUseFPClassFPTrunc`:
```cpp
static Value *simplifyDemandedUseFPClassFPTrunc(InstCombinerImpl &IC,
                                                Instruction &I,
                                                FPClassTest DemandedMask,
                                                KnownFPClass &Known,
                                                unsigned Depth) {
  FPClassTest SrcDemandedMask = DemandedMask;

  // Zero results may have been rounded from subnormal or normal sources.
  if (DemandedMask & fcNegZero)
    SrcDemandedMask |= fcNegSubnormal | fcNegNormal;
  if (DemandedMask & fcPosZero)
    SrcDemandedMask |= fcPosSubnormal | fcPosNormal;

  // Subnormal results may have been normal in the source type
  if (DemandedMask & fcNegSubnormal)
    SrcDemandedMask |= fcNegNormal;
  if (DemandedMask & fcPosSubnormal)
    SrcDemandedMask |= fcPosNormal;

  if (DemandedMask & fcPosInf)
    SrcDemandedMask |= fcPosNormal;
  if (DemandedMask & fcNegInf)
    SrcDemandedMask |= fcNegNormal;

  KnownFPClass KnownSrc;
  if (IC.SimplifyDemandedFPClass(&I, 0, SrcDemandedMask, KnownSrc, Depth + 1))
    return &I;

  Known = KnownFPClass::fptrunc(KnownSrc);

  FPClassTest ValidResults = DemandedMask & Known.KnownFPClasses;
  return getFPClassConstant(I.getType(), ValidResults,
                            /*IsCanonicalizing=*/true);
}
```
Wait, `SrcDemandedMask` is initialized to `DemandedMask`.
Then it adds classes to `SrcDemandedMask` based on `DemandedMask`.
What if `DemandedMask` contains `fcNan`?
If `DemandedMask` contains `fcNan`, `SrcDemandedMask` will contain `fcNan`.
But wait, `fptrunc` can produce `fcNan` from `fcNan` or `fcInf`? No, `fptrunc` of `fcInf` is `fcInf`.
Wait, `fptrunc` of `fcInf` is `fcInf`.
Wait, what if `DemandedMask` contains `fcNan` but not `fcInf`?
If `DemandedMask` contains `fcNan`, `SrcDemandedMask` contains `fcNan`.
But wait, `fptrunc` can produce `fcNan` from `fcNan`.
Can `fptrunc` produce `fcNan` from anything else? No.
Can `fptrunc` produce `fcInf` from anything else? Yes, from `fcNormal` (overflow).
So if `DemandedMask` contains `fcPosInf`, `SrcDemandedMask` adds `fcPosNormal`.
If `DemandedMask` contains `fcNegInf`, `SrcDemandedMask` adds `fcNegNormal`.
What if `DemandedMask` contains `fcPosNormal`?
Does `SrcDemandedMask` need to add anything?
`fptrunc` can produce `fcPosNormal` from `fcPosNormal`.
Can it produce `fcPosNormal` from `fcPosSubnormal`? No, `fptrunc` of subnormal is either subnormal or zero. It cannot be normal.
Wait, what if `DemandedMask` contains `fcPosSubnormal`?
`SrcDemandedMask` adds `fcPosNormal`. Because a normal in the source type can become subnormal in the destination type.
What if `DemandedMask` contains `fcPosZero`?
`SrcDemandedMask` adds `fcPosSubnormal | fcPosNormal`. Because a subnormal or normal in the source type can become zero in the destination type.

Wait, what about `fcNan`?
If `DemandedMask` contains `fcQNan` or `fcSNan`?
Wait, `fptrunc` can quiet a signaling NaN.
So if `DemandedMask` contains `fcQNan`, `SrcDemandedMask` should add `fcSNan`!
Let's check if `simplifyDemandedUseFPClassFPTrunc` handles `fcQNan` -> `fcSNan`.
```cpp
  FPClassTest SrcDemandedMask = DemandedMask;

  // Zero results may have been rounded from subnormal or normal sources.
  if (DemandedMask & fcNegZero)
    SrcDemandedMask |= fcNegSubnormal | fcNegNormal;
  if (DemandedMask & fcPosZero)
