    SrcDemandedMask |= fcNegNormal;
```
Wait, it does NOT add `fcSNan` if `DemandedMask` contains `fcQNan`!
Let's check `InstCombinerImpl::SimplifyDemandedUseFPClass` for `Intrinsic::canonicalize`:
```cpp
    case Intrinsic::canonicalize: {
...
        // A demanded quiet nan result may have come from a signaling nan, so we
        // need to expand the demanded mask.
        if ((DemandedMask & fcQNan) != fcNone)
          SrcDemandedMask |= fcSNan;
```
Ah! `fptrunc` also quiets signaling NaNs!
If `DemandedMask` is `fcQNan`, `SrcDemandedMask` will be `fcQNan`.
Then `SimplifyDemandedFPClass` on the source will assume `fcSNan` is NOT demanded.
If the source is known to be `fcSNan`, `SimplifyDemandedFPClass` might replace it with `poison`!
But `fptrunc` of `fcSNan` is `fcQNan`!
So if we demand `fcQNan` from `fptrunc`, the source could be `fcSNan`. If we don't add `fcSNan` to `SrcDemandedMask`, we might incorrectly optimize the source to `poison`!

Let's verify this.
If `DemandedMask` is `fcQNan`.
`SrcDemandedMask` is `fcQNan`.
`IC.SimplifyDemandedFPClass(&I, 0, SrcDemandedMask, KnownSrc, Depth + 1)`
If the operand is `fcSNan`, `SimplifyDemandedFPClass` will see that `fcSNan` is not in `SrcDemandedMask` (`fcQNan`), so it might replace the operand with `poison` or assume it's never `fcSNan`.
Wait, `SimplifyDemandedFPClass` replaces the operand with `poison` if `Known.isKnownNever(DemandedMask)`.
If the operand is known to be `fcSNan`, `Known.isKnownNever(fcQNan)` is true.
So it will replace the operand with `poison`.
But `fptrunc` of `fcSNan` is `fcQNan`, which satisfies the `DemandedMask` (`fcQNan`)!
So replacing it with `poison` is incorrect!

Let's check if `fptrunc` quiets `fcSNan`.
Yes, IEEE 754 says that any floating-point operation on a signaling NaN quiets it and raises an invalid exception.
LLVM LangRef: "NaN values follow the usual NaN behaviors, except that if a NaN payload is propagated from the input ("Quieting NaN propagation" or "Unchanged NaN propagation" cases), then the low order bits of the NaN payload which cannot fit in the resulting type are discarded."
And "Quieting NaN propagation" means `fcSNan` becomes `fcQNan`.
Let's check `KnownFPClass::fptrunc`:
```cpp
KnownFPClass KnownFPClass::fptrunc(const KnownFPClass &KnownSrc) {
  KnownFPClass Known;

  // Sign should be preserved
  // TODO: Handle cannot be ordered greater than zero
  if (KnownSrc.cannotBeOrderedLessThanZero())
    Known.knownNot(KnownFPClass::OrderedLessThanZeroMask);

  Known.propagateNaN(KnownSrc, true);

  // Infinity needs a range check.
  return Known;
}
```
Wait, `propagateNaN` does:
```cpp
  void propagateNaN(const KnownFPClass &Src, bool PreserveSign = false) {
    if (Src.isKnownNever(fcNan)) {
      knownNot(fcNan);
      if (PreserveSign)
        SignBit = Src.SignBit;
    } else if (Src.isKnownNever(fcSNan))
      knownNot(fcSNan);
  }
```
Wait, `propagateNaN` says: if `Src` is never `fcSNan`, then `Known` is never `fcSNan`.
But if `Src` CAN be `fcSNan`, `Known` CAN be `fcSNan`.
Wait, does `fptrunc` produce `fcSNan`?
No, `fptrunc` quiets `fcSNan`, so the result is `fcQNan`.
Wait, if the payload is truncated and becomes all zeros, it might become `fcInf`? No, LangRef says:
"Note that if discarding the low order bits leads to an all-0 payload, this cannot be represented as a signaling NaN (it would represent an infinity instead), so in that case "Unchanged NaN propagation" is not possible."
Wait, if it becomes all zeros, it becomes `fcInf`? No, it says "this cannot be represented as a signaling NaN (it would represent an infinity instead)". Wait, if it's a quiet NaN, the MSB of the payload is 1, so it cannot become all zeros.
If it's a signaling NaN, the MSB of the payload is 0, and the rest is non-zero. If the rest is truncated to 0, it would become all zeros, which is infinity. BUT IEEE 754 requires the result to be a quiet NaN, so it will set the MSB of the payload to 1. So it becomes a quiet NaN.
So `fptrunc` of `fcSNan` is `fcQNan`.
Wait, `propagateNaN` in `KnownFPClass` does NOT clear `fcSNan` if `Src` can be `fcSNan`. It just says `Known` can be `fcSNan`.
Wait, if `Known` can be `fcSNan`, that's conservative (it says the result might be `fcSNan`).
But for `DemandedMask`, if we demand `fcQNan`, and the source is `fcSNan`, the result WILL be `fcQNan`.
So if `DemandedMask` contains `fcQNan`, we MUST demand `fcSNan` from the source!
Because `fcSNan` in the source will become `fcQNan` in the result, which is demanded.
If we don't add `fcSNan` to `SrcDemandedMask`, we are saying "we don't care what happens if the source is `fcSNan`".
Then `SimplifyDemandedFPClass` might replace the source with `poison` if it's known to be `fcSNan`.
Let's write a test case for this.
```llvm
define float @test_fptrunc_snan_to_qnan(double %x) {
  ; %x is known to be sNaN
  %snan = call double @llvm.arithmetic.fence.f64(double 0x7FF0000000000001) ; sNaN
  %trunc = fptrunc double %snan to float
  ; demand qNaN
  %is_qnan = fcmp uno float %trunc, 0.0
  ...
}
```
Wait, `fcmp uno` demands `fcNan` (both `fcQNan` and `fcSNan`).
To demand ONLY `fcQNan`, we can use `llvm.is.fpclass(..., fcQNan)`.
```llvm
define i1 @test_fptrunc_demand_qnan() {
  %snan = bitcast i64 0x7FF0000000000001 to double ; sNaN
  %trunc = fptrunc double %snan to float
  %class = call i1 @llvm.is.fpclass.f32(float %trunc, i32 2) ; fcQNan is 2? No, fcQNan is 2? Let's check.
}
